    "body": "### Problem\n\nSee steps to reproduce\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a file test.sh with the following content\n```bash\necho \"Hello world\" | while IFS= read -r -n1 c; do\n  printf \"%s\" \"$c\"\n  sleep 0.5\ndone\n```\n2. Open Nvim with ui2 enabled `nvim --clean +\"lua require'vim._core.ui2'.enable{}\"`\n3. Run `:!bash test.sh`\n=> Nvim will block and its screen remains unchanged until the script exits. After that it show the result as\n```\nH\ne\nl\nl\no\n \nw\no\nr\nl\nd\n```\n\nLet's try with ui2 disabled\n4. `nvim --clean`\n5. `:!bash test.sh`\nWhile also blocking, Nvim still update screen every 0.5s to add each character \"H\", \"e\", \"l\", etc to the pager (so you can feel like someone is typing in the pager). After the command exits, it shows correct output of the command\n```\nHello world\n```\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nUI2 version should stream output, and must display them correctly\n\nStreaming output is quite important for `grep` command IMO, so you can stop the command with Ctrl-C when it already found the result you want.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-dev-5048d9aa2a\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nNA\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nNA\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nNA\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nNA\n\n### Installation\n\nNA",
