        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "It's not specifically about grep, but about any streamed output where you want to monitor the output. For an example, consider\n```bash\n# save as temp.sh\nfor i in {1..100}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\n  sleep 0.1\ndone\n```\nand run it using ```:!./temp.sh```.  I quoted the `grep` in the original issue as the reason for why I asked the question. I think @luukvbaal's comment \"but scrolling to the bottom probably makes more sense\" would be a good option/default. It is also how ~cmdline~messages (Not sure about the correct term here) presently works, though I'm fine if you want to change the defaults.\n\nAdditionally, `te` may be a solution for the above, but is not a solution for `make` or `grep`. Commands like `grep` and `make` in vim/neovim allow to use the qflist(`]c`, `[c`, `cdo`...), which `te` doesn't allow(as far as I know, correct me if I'm wrong).\n\nEdit: For completeness, you can't `g<`, because this blocks neovim.",
